<HEAD>
<TITLE>Sharpening the Tools of US Foreign Policy - Issues '96 - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 19</h3>
<center><h2>SHARPENING THE TOOLS OF U.S. FOREIGN POLICY</B></P>
<P>
<b><CITE>By <a href="/heritage/staff/moore.html">Thomas G. Moore</a>, Thomas P. Sheehy, <a href="/heritage/staff/johnson.htm">Bryan T. Johnson</a>, <a href="/heritage/staff/hillen.html">John Hillen</a>, John Dori, and Brett Schaefer</CITE></b>
<p>
<a href="chpt19.html#un">The United Nations</a> | <a href="chpt19.html#int">Intelligence Gathering and Covert Operations</a> | <a href="chpt19.html#for">Foreign Aid</a> | <a href="chpt19.html#pub">Public Diplomacy</a> | <a href="chpt19.html#EXP">Experts</a>
</center><p>

<P>Beyond the traditional tools of statecraft  war and diplomacy   America has
many lesser tools at its disposal in formulating  and executing foreign policy.
Like all good tools, however, they  are means to an end and should be used only
under the right  circumstances and with proper care. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>One of these tools is the United Nations. The U.S. should treat  the U.N.
not as some superior body to which it must apply for  approval, but as an
institution which can be useful in cultivating  international support for U.S.
policy. Another tool is foreign aid.  Aid can be an effective adjunct to U.S.
foreign policy, but only if  it works and serves American interests, neither of
which it has  done very well. Two other tools, both of which are indispensable 
for national security, are intelligence gathering and covert  operations. Even
though the Cold War is over, the chaotic and  threatening condition of today's
world requires a robust and effective  intelligence capability. Finally, there
is the important work of  public diplomacy, as represented by the United States 
Information Agency (USIA), the Voice of America (VOA), and other  official
media. Telling the American story to people overseas helps  build international
support for democracy and freedom, as well as  for specific U.S. policies.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America must be engaged in world affairs. The U.S. cannot  protect its vital
interests unless it seeks to influence world opinion  and events in such
international bodies as the United Nations. But  this does not mean compromising
American principles, sovereignty,  or freedom of action. Whether in the U.N. or
any other  multilateral organization, the U.S. government should strive to
protect  American interests and represent American values. America must  pursue
its own agenda, not that of international bureaucrats often  hostile to U.S
interests. Only by doing so can the United States  remain strong enough to
contribute effectively to international peace  and stability.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>How to develop this American agenda in international  diplomacy is an issue
which separates conservatives from liberals.  Liberals tend to distrust American
power and seek to constrain it by tying  it to the U.N. Conservatives, knowing
that this power historically  has been used for good, want to liberate it from
these constraints.  Liberals want to put American forces under U.N. military 
command, and to have America adopt the U.N. bureaucracy's generally  socialist
agenda as its own; some have gone so far as to propose  that the U.N. be given
taxing powers over U.S. citizens. By  contrast, conservatives want America to
retain sovereign control over  its own military forces when they are involved in
U.N.  peacekeeping operations. Above all, conservatives want to prevent the U.S.
 from becoming a mere servant of the U.N.'s agenda, as the Clinton 
Administration has allowed to happen in Somalia and elsewhere;  they are willing
to work through the U.N. when it suits American  interests, but not when these
interests are not served.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Another issue is whether, and to what extent, to support  U.S. policy abroad
through public diplomacy. Most people believe  that 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->  the U.S. needs some form of public
diplomacy to explain  American policy and values to people in foreign lands. It
is well  known that Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty and the Voice of  America
played important roles in bringing down the Iron Curtain.  What role should they
play in today's international diplomacy?   And once this role has been
established, what is the best way to  convey this message, through existing
official media structures and  outlets or through new ones?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
<a name="un">
<center>
<P><h2>THE UNITED NATIONS</h2>
<A HREF="chpt19.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt19.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt19.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt19.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A>
</center><P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>

<P>Even its strongest advocates recognize that the U.N. is  bloated, wasteful,
poorly managed, and disorganized. Only  fundamental reform can reinvigorate the
U.N. and restore its lost  credibility. The Clinton Administration itself
recognizes that unless the  U.N. is reformed, it will drift into irrelevance and
lose public support. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The U.N. claims that the U.S. is some $1.3 billion behind in  its financial
contributions. Washington says the figure should  be somewhat less. With
approximately half of its 185 member  states delinquent in their dues, the U.N.
is in serious financial crisis.  The Clinton Administration wants to pay, but
Congress wants to  withhold payment until the U.N. gets its budget under control
and  ends corruption and poor management practices. The Clinton  Administration
may propose a deal with Congress to repay America's  back fees over several
years in return for promised U.N. reforms.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Over the past few years, the U.N. has proven that it cannot  manage 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  large, complex, and ambitious &quot;peace
operations&quot;  competently. This was seen most clearly in the debacles in
Somalia and  the former Yugoslavia. Not only have these operations been 
spectacular failures; they have been costly in terms of lives, material 
resources, and money. The U.S. spent almost $3 billion (in  direct and indirect
costs) in 1995 to support these failed U.N. operations. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Another contentious issue involves the specialized agencies.  Conservatives
believe that agencies such as the United Nations  Development Program (UNDP) and
United Nations Industrial  Development Organization (UNIDO) do not merit
American financial  support or membership. Not only are they poorly managed and 
wasteful, but their mandates are counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     There is broad consensus that the U.N. needs
reforming.  Secretary of State Warren Christopher, in a September 1995 address
to  the U.N. General Assembly, proposed a &quot;concrete agenda&quot; for  U.N.
reform. This agenda involves ending programs that have  achieved their purpose,
consolidating overlapping programs,  downsizing regional economic commissions,
and imposing a moratorium  on big conferences.<A
HREF="ftnt19.htm#1">1</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Funding for the U.N. system falls into two categories:
assessed  and voluntary contributions. An assessed contribution is the price  of
membership in the U.N. and its specialized agencies.  Countries make voluntary
contributions to specialized agencies they  also wish to support. For 1996, the
Clinton Administration  requested some $1.07 billion for U.S. assessed and
voluntary contributions  to the U.N. and its specialized agencies and
commissions.  Actual 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  U.S. spending for these
organizations totaled $1 billion in  1994. By contrast, more than 90 other
countries together account for  less than 1 percent of the U.N. budget, paying
only .01 percent each.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Cases of fraud and abuse erupt with disturbing regularity. In 
1995, for example, $10 million was embezzled from the United  Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) in Kenya. Various agencies of  the U.N. spent approximately $1
million a day at the height of the  Somalia peacekeeping operation in 1993. This
included renting  hundreds of apartments equipped with air conditioning. In 
December 1995, the U.N. scrapped a never-used $1 million turnstile  security
system at its New York headquarters. The reason: The  turnstile clocks would
have tracked the arrival and departure times of  U.N. employees. In 1995, the
U.N. spent some $500,000 for a  two-week conference on the Sustainable
Development of Small Island  Developing States, including $15,000 to fly
representatives from  the Western Sahara to Barbados.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The U.N. has grown into a massive bureaucracy of over 70 
agencies and programs, including the United Nations Research  Institute for
Social Development (UNRISD) and the International  Labor Organization (ILO),
with overlapping mandates. The U.N.  system has over 50,000 employees. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The United States plays a key role in supporting U.N. 
peacekeeping. Until last year, the U.S. paid nearly one-third of the  annual
$3.5 billion peacekeeping bill (now unilaterally reduced to 25  percent). The
U.S. assigns thousands of American soldiers to  U.N. missions and provides
billions of dollars worth of  transportation, equipment, and other support
services to the U.N. at no charge.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Until recently, traditional U.N. peacekeeping operations 
entailed small observation or peacekeeping missions deployed to  monitor an
already existing peace settlement. These operations  were simple, inexpensive,
unambitious, and usually staffed by  countries like Canada, Sweden, Norway, or
Austria. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     With the end of Cold War tensions among members of the 
Security Council, there was an explosion in peacekeeping  operations from 1989
to 1993, with the Security Council authorizing  more missions than it had in the
previous 40 years. In 1990, the  U.N. controlled approximately 10,000 &quot;blue
helmets&quot; in eight  operations at a cost of less than $700 million per year.
By the end  of 1993, there were over 90,000 &quot;blue helmets&quot; in 18
different  operations costing over $3.5 billion per year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The U.N. has conducted 21 observation missions and six 
traditional peacekeeping missions since 1948. These missions have  a mixed
record in limiting armed conflict and promoting  conflict resolution. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The U.N. has expanded the definition of peacekeeping 
significantly since 1990. Now peacekeeping is called &quot;second  generation
peacekeeping&quot; or &quot;peace-enforcement.&quot;  In these  operations,
peacekeepers have been sent to volatile and dangerous areas  (such as Somalia
and Bosnia) before a conclusive peace was  achieved. These missions have been
large (employing up to 40,000  troops); complex (involving armored combat
formations with combat  air and naval support); dangerous (resulting in hundreds
of  U.N. troops killed in Somalia and Bosnia); ambitious (attempting  to impose
peace through force of arms); and expensive (costing  the U.N. almost $5 million
per day in Bosnia). All have been failures. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     As of August 1995, the U.S. had over 3,200 American troops 
deployed in support of U.N. peacekeeping operations. These  operations include
Macedonia, Western Sahara, Kuwait, and Haiti.  The U.S. also provided the great
bulk of NATO air forces to enforce  a U.N.-sponsored &quot;no-fly zone&quot;
over Bosnia-Herzegovina  from 1993 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Peacekeeping operations harm U.S. combat readiness. Time 
spent on peacekeeping missions is time not spent learning or  rehearsing
critical warfighting skills. A recent General Accounting  Office report noted
the deleterious effects of peacekeeping on  readiness,<A
HREF="ftnt19.htm">2</A> documenting how it can take 12 to 18
months for a unit to return  to the minimum proficiency standards required by
U.S. doctrine.  This means, for instance, that the U.S. Army in Europe, which
has  deployed most of its units to Bosnia for peace implementation  duty, will
be out of the warfighting business for two to three years.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The U.N. cannot command and control most military operations. 
It does not have the legitimacy, authority, structure, or procedures  to
organize and direct military missions competently. U.N.  command and control is
characterized by confusion and unresponsiveness.  A prime example is the
incoherent command and control  structure used in Somalia. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The U.S. withdrew from the Paris-based United Nations 
Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) in  1984 because of
its hostility to free markets and record of waste  and abuse.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In January 1996, the U.S. Army court-martialed Specialist 
Michael 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 -->  New. Specialist New had refused to
wear a U.N. beret and  insignia when his unit was deployed on U.N. duty in
Macedonia,  maintaining that he swore an oath of allegiance to the U.S.
Constitution  and not to the U.N. However, under U.S. law, up to 1,000 U.S. 
soldiers can be deployed at any one time in U.N. missions. Specialist  New swore
an oath to follow all legal orders and was treated fairly,  but his case raises
the broader issue of U.S. participation in U.N.  military missions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Secretary General Boutros-Ghali in January 1996 mentioned  the
possibility that the U.N. might impose a tax on such activities  as
international air travel and currency exchanges to gain &quot;a  minimum of
independence&quot; from member nations. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration began with a great deal of  enthusiasm for the
United Nations. President Clinton and his team  believed that with the end of
the Cold War, the U.N. could be  reinvigorated and begin to live up to the lofty
language of its Charter,  which assumes a central role for the organization in
preserving peace  and international security. The Clinton plan was for America
to  provide considerable support for U.N. peacekeeping and other  activities,
including foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration initially embraced an  interventionist U.N. Under
the doctrine of &quot;assertive multilateralism,&quot; the  U.S. would advance
its security goals by working &quot;assertively&quot; with  the U.N. rather than
unilaterally or with allies. Central to this  approach was heavy American
support of U.N. peacekeeping. U.N.  Secretary General Boutros Boutros-Ghali went
so far as to advocate  a 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  standing U.N. army under his
control. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>President Clinton was forced to retreat from this doctrine after  the
failure of the U.N. operation in Somalia, where the U.N.  undertook an ambitious
nation-building mandate for which it was  unprepared. In support of this
mission, President Clinton deployed U.S.  Army Rangers who were assigned to
capture a Somali warlord for  the U.N. In October 1993, American soldiers were
drawn into a  street battle in Mogadishu during which 18 Americans were killed 
and 75 wounded. In May 1994, Clinton backtracked and issued  Presidential
Decision Directive 25 (PDD 25), placing restrictions  on U.S. participation in
U.N. peacekeeping. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The highlight of the Clinton Administration's U.N. reform  effort has been
to establish an Inspector General's office in New  York. For years, Congress has
been pushing this idea. Unfortunately,  this office has only limited scope and
has been characterized as a  &quot;disappointment&quot; by Representative Lee
Hamilton (D-IN) and  Senator Nancy Kassebaum (R-KS), two Members of Congress who
 have long championed the U.N. Driven by budget constraints,  the Clinton
Administration in December 1995 announced the  long-overdue U.S. withdrawal from
the United Nations Industrial  Development Organization (UNIDO).
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 104th Congress tried to restrict some of the more  egregious Clinton
policies toward the U.N. The House and Senate  passed separate bills in 1995
that would cut U.S. financial contributions  to U.N. peacekeeping and limit U.S.
forces deployed in U.N.  peacekeeping operations. Both bills embody provisions
of the  Contract With America. During negotiations with the Clinton 
Administration, language in the defense authorization bill that placed  limits 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  on U.S. participation in U.N.
peacekeeping was dropped.  President Clinton claimed that these limits were a
challenge to his  authority as commander in chief and threatened to veto the
bill if it  contained any such language. Congress backed down and passed  a
defense bill without these restrictions in January 1996. The  President
subsequently signed the defense bill.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>On another front, Representative Joe Scarborough (R-FL) in  October 1995
introduced the United Nations Withdrawal Act. This  legislation would require
the U.S. to withdraw from the U.N. by  the year 2000, retaining its membership
only in the U.N.'s  independent and specialized agencies. Representative
Scarborough's  bill was referred to the International Relations Committee, where
 it remains under consideration. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration boasts frequently of its participation  in
U.N.-sponsored international conferences. Vice President Al  Gore went to the
Cairo Conference on Population and Development  in 1994 and accompanied Hillary
Clinton to the Copenhagen  Social Summit in 1995, and Mrs. Clinton and Health
and Human  Services Secretary Donna Shalala attended the 1995 Fourth Women's 
Conference in Beijing. These conferences have come under  heavy criticism, both
for their anti-Western agendas and for their  wastefulness.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In early 1996, Secretary General Boutros-Ghali floated the idea  of imposing
a U.N. tax on member nations. Republican  Senators Robert Dole (KS) and Jesse
Helms (NC) responded in January  by introducing legislation to bar U.S. payments
to the U.N. if it  tries to implement such a tax. The Clinton Administration
opposes  a U.N. tax.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>To promote U.S. interests in the U.N. without sacrificing 
American sovereignty or effectiveness, and to ensure that America  does not get
dragged into unworkable peacekeeping operations, the  U.S. should: 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Limit its total non-peacekeeping contribution to no more  than
$500 million per year.</B> In 1995, America's assessed and  voluntary
contributions to the U.N. and its specialized agencies and  commissions totaled
some $1 billion. Approximately $260 million of  this amount went to the U.N.
administrative budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Stop paying assessed contributions to U.N. specialized  agencies.</B>
The few specialized agencies worthy of support, such as the  Universal Postal
Union and the World Meteorological  Organization, should be funded on a
case-by-case and voluntary basis from  the $500 million given to the U.N. This
dramatically reduced level  of spending will allow the U.S. to establish a
fundamentally  different relationship with a considerably scaled-back U.N.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Never place U.S. troops under U.N. command.</B> The U.S.  may
choose to support some traditional peacekeeping operations,  such as the one in
Cyprus. However, U.S. forces should not be  placed under U.N. command. The U.S.
can provide support for U.N.  missions without operating in the U.N. chain of
command. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Never give the Security Council veto power over American  foreign
policy.</B> It may be diplomatically useful to gain U.N.  Security Council
support for U.S. military actions, as President Bush did  in 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  the Persian Gulf War when his
Administration won a  Security Council resolution supporting the expulsion of
Iraq from  Kuwait. However, this support should never be considered essential. 
The U.S. should never allow Security Council politics to keep it  from defending
vital American interests.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Eliminate funding for the United Nations Development  Program
(UNDP).</B> One of the bewildering array of specialized agencies  in the U.N.
system, UNDP is charged with &quot;contribut[ing] to a  sustainable expansion of
the world economy.&quot;  Essentially, it is a  foreign aid agency. Not only are
its programs unfocused and  duplicative, but foreign aid has proven
counterproductive in country  after country. Eliminating funding for this
specialized agency will  save the U.S. approximately $120 million a year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     End funding for all U.N. international conferences.</B> These 
conferences, which cost millions of dollars, are long on rhetoric  and short on
achievement. The 1995 Social Summit, for example,  focused on &quot;Creating
Jobs&quot; and &quot;Building Solidarity,&quot; two  objectives well beyond the
capabilities of a one-time gathering of  national and international bureaucrats.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*      Reject any proposal to vest the U.N. with taxing authority.</B> 
Senators Dole and Helms have introduced legislation that would  have the U.S.
stop paying its dues if the U.N. tries to impose a tax.  The Clinton
Administration also has voiced its opposition to the idea  of such a tax. The
U.S. should continue to send a strong message  that this trial balloon, floated
by Secretary General Boutros-Ghali  in January 1996 and bound to resurface
within the U.N., is  unacceptable. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Isn't it isolationist to suggest that the U.S. reduce its role in 
the U.N.? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> No. Opposition to a poorly managed and corrupt  international
bureaucracy in New York is not support for isolationism.  Conservatives support
NATO and other alliances, as well as limited  participation in the U.N. This is
not isolationist; it is international  engagement in support of American, not
U.N., interests.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Why are you so opposed to the U.N.?  What right do we have  to impose
our will without first consulting with the  international community through the
U.N.? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> When deciding American foreign policy, the President  should
consult with his advisors and the Congress, not the U.N. We  don't need the
permission of the U.N. to protect American freedom  and interests. The U.N. is
plagued with corruption, and many of  its activities, including its foreign aid
programs, perpetuate  dependency throughout the developing world. Moreover, the
U.N.  is merely a collection of often opposing national interests. It is 
ridiculous to suggest that the 180-plus governments in the U.N.   many of which
are dictatorships  represent the democratic will  of the world community.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. The U.N. is responsible for international peace and  security. How
can the U.S. promote international peace and security if it  is not involved in
U.N. peacekeeping? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Despite its lofty objectives, the U.N. contributes only  margin
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 -->  ally to international peace and
security. Since its creation in  1945, it has been a bit player on the world
stage. The U.S. remains  the world's principal force for international peace and
security  by maintaining forces in Europe and the Pacific region and by 
participating in alliance structures like NATO. It is highly misleading  to
measure a nation's contribution to the world's security by  gauging its
participation in marginal undertakings like U.N.  peacekeeping. America and its
Western allies ended the Cold War by being  militarily strong, not by
participating in &quot;peace&quot; missions  sponsored by the U.N. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. An American soldier, Specialist Michael New, was  court-martialed in
January 1996 for refusing to wear U.N. insignia  and serve under U.N. command.
He maintains this violates his oath  to support and defend the Constitution of
the United States. Do  you support him?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> As a soldier, Specialist New is obligated by his oath to obey 
the lawful orders of his chain of command. However unwise as a  matter of
policy, New's orders were not illegal. Therefore, he  should face the
consequences of his disobedience. However,  Specialist New should not have been
placed in a position where he  was forced to choose between his duty and his
conscience.  American soldiers should not be placed in the U.N. chain of
command.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Secretary General Boutros-Ghali has floated the idea of  establishing
a U.N. tax on international commercial airline flights,  currency exchanges, and
other international transactions. What do  you think about this?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> It is ridiculous. The power to tax is a sovereign power of  gov
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 -->  ernment, which is accountable to
the people in a free society.  The U.N. is accountable to no one but member
governments and  bureaucrats. The U.N. has no sovereignty over its member
states;  nor should it ever have such power. The U.N. is the creation and  the
servant of its member states. In any case, its problems stem  not from a lack of
money, but from having too much money. It is  very disturbing that Secretary
General Boutros-Ghali and others  within the U.N. are trying to make this power
grab.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. In the first session of the 104th Congress, legislation was 
introduced to pull the U.S. out of the U.N. Why not go all the way  and simply
take the U.S. out of the U.N.?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The Security Council can serve some useful purposes. At  times,
for example, it can be a forum for discussion of important  international
issues. However, the U.S. should never feel constrained  by Security Council
resolutions, and U.S. participation in the U.  N. should be scaled back. A major
cut in U.S. funding would go  a long way toward achieving this goal. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
<a name="int">
<center><H2>INTELLIGENCE GATHERING AND COVERT OPERATIONS</H2>
<P>
<A HREF="chpt19.html#ISSUESI">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt19.html#FACTSI">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt19.html#RECORDI">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt19.html#Q&AI">Q&amp;A</A>
</center>
<P><B><A NAME="ISSUESI">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Effective intelligence is as necessary today as during the  Cold War.
Despite the end of the Cold War, the world remains a  very dangerous and
increasingly unpredictable place. Threats  to America's interests are real and
growing. They can arise in  regions vital to the U.S. with little or no warning.
America needs a  robust 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  intelligence gathering capacity
both to enable its leaders to  understand these threats and to give them as much
warning of  approaching danger as possible. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>However, the U.S. intelligence community today faces  serious problems and
challenges. The morale of the Central  Intelligence Agency has been severely
damaged by the Aldrich Ames spy  case. Moreover, the CIA has failed to predict
crucially important  developments, most notably the collapse of the Soviet Union
 and Saddam Hussein's invasion of Kuwait. The intelligence  community, like the
Defense Department, has been forced to  finance much of the so-called peace
dividend through drastic reductions  in budgets and personnel. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Many issues must be resolved if the U.S. is to maintain robust  and highly
capable intelligence assets able to meet the complex  challenges of the
post-Cold War era and the 21st century. Among  the questions facing policymakers
today:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Can the intelligence services
continue to do their job in the face  of deep budget cuts?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     To what degree should human means of gathering
intelligence,  as opposed to technical means such as satellites, be emphasized?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     How much should the intelligence services be
scaled back  now that the Cold War is over?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     How should the intelligence services deal with
such post-Cold  War threats as the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction,
 terrorism, narcotics trafficking, and the growing prominence of  rogue 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 -->  states in threatening
international peace and stability?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     What is the proper role for covert operations?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     Should the CIA be involved in non-traditional
kinds of  espionage, such as spying on foreign businesses?
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTSI">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     The U.S. intelligence community consists of the
Central  Intelligence Agency; the Defense Intelligence Agency; the  intelligence
units of the armed services; the National Security Agency,  which monitors and
analyzes worldwide radio-telephone and other  electronic transmissions; and the
National Reconnaissance  Office, which gathers and processes satellite imagery.
The CIA is  forbidden by law to conduct intelligence activities inside the U.S.;
 domestic intelligence and internal security are the responsibility  of the
Federal Bureau of Investigation. Overall coordination and  direction of foreign
intelligence is provided by the Director of  Central Intelligence (DCI),
although military intelligence operates  with a high degree of autonomy within
this structure. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The DCI is appointed by the President and confirmed by the 
Senate, which means the CIA is subject to a certain degree of  political
pressure from the White House. Ideally, however, the DCI is  objective and &quot;non-political,&quot;
since intelligence findings tailored  to fit political objectives can be
useless, if not actually dangerous  and misleading.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Most U.S. intelligence on foreign activities is derived from 
monitoring electronic emissions (radio and telephone traffic) and  from 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 -->  satellites orbiting high above
the Earth. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Information gained from satellites is vital, especially in 
wartime. Satellites allow the U.S. to detect and track missile launches;  to
track the movements of foreign ground, air, and naval forces;  and to monitor
compliance with arms control treaties. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Although America's intelligence collection from satellites 
and signals intercepts is highly effective, the U.S. intelligence  community
relies heavily on high technology and neglects  intelligence from human sources
(HUMINT). There is no substitute for  the information provided by trained or
knowledgeable human  observers. People can enter underground or covered
facilities which  satellite sensors cannot observe. Only people can penetrate 
terrorist cells or drug networks, and only human agents can provide  some
assessment of an adversary's intentions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Much of the U.S. intelligence budget is classified; the 
amount spent on &quot;black&quot; (clandestine) programs is not available. 
However, the unclassified intelligence budget is approximately $28  billion
annually.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORDI">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration has failed to resolve these  fundamental issues,
or even to undertake any serious reappraisal  of America's intelligence needs.
Nor has Clinton been able to  improve CIA morale in the wake of the Aldrich Ames
disaster.  Instead, the Administration has presided over a reduction of 
intelligence agency budgets and personnel without any clear rationale  or
understanding of the changing role of intelligence in the  post-Cold 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  War world. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The intelligence community is being downsized at a rate of  3-5 percent per
year, with some vital components losing as much as  80 percent of their
personnel. Moreover, the Administration has  failed to recognize that the
national intelligence mission has not  diminished substantially with the end of
the Cold War; it has  become broader and more complex. While reducing its
resources, the  Administration continues to impose on the intelligence community
 a growing range of tasks, such as supporting arms control and  other
international agreements being pursued by the White House  and monitoring
developments in trouble spots like Somalia,  Rwanda, Haiti, and the Balkans
where the Administration has  committed U.S. forces to peacekeeping and
humanitarian missions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>By demanding more of the intelligence community while  cutting its
resources, the Clinton Administration is in danger of  stretching America's
intelligence capabilities to the breaking point.  The President is jeopardizing
the intelligence community's ability  to provide strategic warning in the event
of conflict and to  furnish vital analysis to the national command authority in
time of crisis.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Another problem is that the Administration has politicized the  CIA by &quot;cooking&quot;
intelligence findings to support preconceived  positions. Perhaps the most
glaring example has been  the Administration's attempt to downplay the ballistic
missile threat  to the continental United States in order to justify its
opposition  to national missile defense<B>.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997
</B><!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To ensure that America's intelligence services are adequately  supported and
prepared to deal with tomorrow's threats to  American security, the
Administration and Congress should:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Stabilize the budget, personnel, and
technical resources of the  intelligence community.</B> Congress should direct
the  Administration to conduct a thorough assessment of the types of
intelligence  and levels of activity that are vital to national security, and
then to  base budget and manpower decisions on that assessment. So far,  this
has not been done.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Shore up the human side of espionage. </B> Because
America's  high technology is superior, the intelligence community has 
developed a strong technocratic bias. It often neglects the human side of 
intelligence gathering. Technical intelligence is valuable, but it has  its
limits. Only people can get inside an underground weapons  storage facility or,
more important, get inside the thinking of a  potential aggressor or penetrate a
terrorist cell. Improving human  intelligence will require institutional change
that assures career  advancement for officers who are aggressive in recruiting
and  &quot;running&quot; informants and operatives and that allows agency
officers to  use commonsense criteria in recruiting foreign operatives and 
informants. Common sense suggests that foreign informants  sometimes will be
unsavory characters. As long as these informants do  not harm Americans, the
U.S. should not assume responsibility for  all their actions merely because they
are informants or working  on contract. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Generate more innovation and creativity in the 
intelligence services.</B> Gathering foreign intelligence is as much an art as a
 science. The problem with U.S. intelligence is not lack of data,  but lack of
imagination and creativity in concluding what the data  are 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 -->  saying, in discerning the
patterns and trends suggested by the  data. The CIA needs to reward agents in
the field for innovative  collection methods. It also needs to reward analysts
for foresight,  insight, and good judgment in drawing proper conclusions from
the  information collected. The DCI must not merely manage the  Agency but lead
it. That means ending the mindset of risk-averse,  bureaucratic caution that
dominates the CIA. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Strengthen the CIA's counter-intelligence  capabilities</B>. There must
be no more Ames-like penetrations of the CIA. This will  require an internal or
institutional change in thinking which  accepts the possibility that U.S.
intelligence agencies are targets for  foreign penetration and that,
regrettably, some Americans like  Ames can be recruited to betray their country.
Better congressional  oversight which demands accountability by CIA managers,
and  support by the DCI and the Agency for a vigorous  counter-intelligence
effort inside the Agency, are also necessary for improving 
counter-intelligence.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Better control the dissemination of intelligence not
only to  allies, but also to the U.N.</B> The Clinton Administration's decision
to  share U.S. intelligence could cripple America's ability to collect 
intelligence by compromising the sources and methods used to  gather
information. Congress should severely restrict, if not forbid,  the disclosure
of U.S. intelligence to non-alliance organizations  like the U.N.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&AI">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Why do we need spies now that the Cold War is over?
</B><!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> America and its allies still face a variety of threats and  new
challenges to vital interests even though the Cold War is over.  The radical
downsizing of U.S. military forces makes it more  crucial than ever that America
have the best possible intelligence, both  to provide early warning of crisis to
the commander in chief and  to provide policy options for dealing with the
complex new  challenges of the post-Cold War world.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. With the end of the Soviet military threat, wouldn't U.S. 
intelligence assets be put to better use gathering information  on America's
competition in technology and trade?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The U.S. government needs to stay out of corporate  espionage.
Some argue that the U.S., while no longer engaged in a  military confrontation
with the Soviet Union, should see itself as  engaged in an economic war with
rest of the world. Such claims are  alarmist at least, and deceptive at best. If
American corporations want  to engage in the normal and legal gathering of
business  information, that is their choice. But diverting U.S. government 
intelligence agencies to spy for U.S. business risks discrediting  the
government's legitimate function. Recent allegations that the  CIA spied for the
United State Trade Representative's office  during automotive negotiations with
Japan are a case in point. Instead  of spying for American corporations, which
are private entities  not deserving of official support, intelligence agencies
should  be monitoring the sales of Russian nuclear weapons and the  movements of
Iranian submarines operating in the Persian Gulf. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Why does the CIA use criminals and murderers as agents  in Latin
America and other Third World countries, even  including some allegedly guilty
of killing American citizens?
</B><!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Informants are not the same as field officers, or what  are
loosely termed &quot;agents.&quot;  No one would hold a New York  policeman
responsible for the actions of a drug dealer turned  informant, especially if
the offending actions have nothing to do with the  undercover operation. The
same is true regarding CIA  informants. However, under no circumstances should
the CIA protect an  informant or contract employee who harms a fellow American. 
When such cases come to light, the Agency should terminate the  relationship at
once and report the criminal to the proper authorities,  even if it means losing
a valuable source of information.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
<a name="for">
<CENTER><H2>FOREIGN AID</H2>
<P>
<A HREF="chpt19.html#ISSUESF">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt19.html#FACTSF">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt19.html#RECORDF">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt19.html#Q&AF">Q&amp;A</A>
</center>
<P><A NAME="ISSUESF"><B>THE ISSUES
</B></A></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>America's foreign aid program is coming under increasing  scrutiny, not only
by the American public, but also in Congress.  Although the $12 billion a year
spent on foreign aid represents a  relatively small part of the federal budget,
more and more  skeptics argue that this program is a waste of taxpayers' money.
There  is little evidence to support the contentions of proponents that  foreign
aid is vital to America's national interest. There is even  less evidence that
this money actually helps alleviate poverty in  less-developed countries.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Why, then, has foreign aid proved to be one of the hardest  programs to cut
or eliminate?  The main reason is the way the  program is structured. The
foreign aid program has three major  elements. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>First</B> is military and security assistance to promote
America's  national security abroad. Consisting of such undertakings as 
anti-narcotics efforts, joint military training exercises between U.S.  and
foreign forces, and grants to foreign countries to purchase  U.S. military
equipment, this program accounts for about 25 percent  of the overall foreign
aid budget. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Second</B> is humanitarian and disaster relief assistance to aid 
victims of natural disaster and prevent mass starvation. This program  accounts
for some 15 percent of the foreign aid budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Third</B> is economic and development assistance to promote  economic
growth in less developed countries. This program  consumes about 60 percent of
the foreign aid budget. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The debate over foreign aid often has centered on funding  levels for these
three major components. During the Cold War, the  U.S. funneled significant
amounts of military and security aid, as  well as economic and development
assistance, to its allies in the  fight against communism. Now that the Soviet
Union has  collapsed, however, critics of the program wonder why America needs 
to spend $12 billion a year around the globe. The Clinton  Administration argues
that the program is still needed to support  America's interests abroad.
Skeptics, many of whom questioned the merits  of the economic aid program even
during the Cold War, argue that  it makes even less sense today.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Many proposals have surfaced, from abolishing the Agency  for International
Development (AID), the agency in charge of  distributing America's foreign aid
dollars, to moving remaining  funding 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  and programs into existing
departments like State and  Defense. Another &quot;reform&quot; proposal would
increase the budget to face  the new challenges of the post-Cold War era and
re-focus the  program on what is called &quot;sustainable economic development&quot;
of  poorer countries. This is the argument made by the Clinton  Administration.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTSF">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     The U.S. spends about $12 billion a year on
foreign aid.  However, this amount does not include such other commitments as
the  $40 billion bailout of the Mexican economy; the money spent on  military
exercises like the operations in Somalia, Rwanda, and  Haiti; and long-term
funding, capital obligations, and  &quot;replenishments funds&quot; (in addition
to the annual appropriations) for such  institutions as the World Bank, the
International Monetary Fund, and  the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     There are 156 countries that receive foreign aid from the U.S.
 The largest recipients are Israel, which gets some $3 billion a year,  and
Egypt, which gets some $2 billion a year. These two  countries alone make up
some 40 percent of the entire foreign aid budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Military and security assistance accounts for about 25 percent
 of all aid, humanitarian and disaster relief assistance about 15  percent, and
economic and development assistance about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Of the 64 countries receiving U.S. foreign aid for at least 35
 years (many for as long as 51 years), 41 have economies that either  have
remained essentially the same or have shrunk since 1965. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Countries that have developed over the last three decades 
have done so without foreign aid.<B> </B>The so-called Asian Tigers  (Hong
Kong, Singapore, Taiwan, and South Korea) are among the  fastest growing and
most prosperous economies in the world. Thirty  years ago, they were poor. Yet
after implementing a number of  economic reforms, such as cutting taxes and
regulations and  privatizing businesses, they grew quickly. This growth took
place  without the infusion of foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Most U.S. foreign aid never reaches the poor and the children 
of less developed countries. Over 70 cents of every U.S. dollar  spent on
foreign aid to help the world's poor stays in the United States.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORDF">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There is bipartisan consensus that foreign aid needs to be  reformed. The
Clinton Administration's own study on  reinventing government argues that AID
does not have a single, clearly  defined and articulated strategic mission.
Shortly after this study  was issued, Secretary of State Warren Christopher
announced his  proposal for an enhanced Department of International Relations 
in which AID and other agencies would be abolished and their  functions assumed
by the State Department.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The State Department authorization bill would have moved  USIA, the Arms
Control and Disarmament Agency (ACDA), and  AID into the State Department. The
bill was derailed by  opposition from the Clinton Administration and Senate
Democrats, led  by Senator John Kerry (D-MA). The House of Representatives 
approved these consolidations in June 1995, and Senator Kerry  and Senate
Foreign Relations Committee chairman Jesse Helms  (R-
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 -->  NC) agreed to a plan to cut the
operating expenses of these  agencies. Consolidation proponents believe that
these cuts will  force the Clinton Administration to move these three agencies
into  the State Department. A House-Senate conference report awaits  approval by
the Senate and the President, who has threatened to  veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 1996 appropriations bill for foreign aid has been passed  by both houses
of Congress and signed by the President. This  measure cuts foreign aid spending
from $14.3 billion in FY 1995 to  $12.1 billion in FY 1996. The 1996
appropriations bill also includes  language requiring AID to submit to Congress
a detailed report  outlining the relative levels of economic freedom of foreign
aid  recipients. This report will make it more difficult for AID to  continue to
give money to countries with economically unfree or  repressed economies.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While a great deal has been done to curtail wasteful foreign  aid spending,
much remains to be done. In 1997, the  Administration and Congress should:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     Phase out corporate welfare.</B> America's corporate
welfare  system, which includes the Export-Import Bank and the Overseas  Private
Investment Corporation, diverts money from the pockets of  the American taxpayer
to preferred big businesses. Coddling of  private business by the U.S.
government with tax dollars is not  needed. America already is the largest
exporter in the world, and most  of its exporting companies are doing very well
indeed without  corporate welfare. These funds would be spent far better if left
in  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->  wallets of the American taxpayer.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Abolish the Agency for International Development, along  with most
of its functions, and move any remaining functions to  the State Department.</B>
AID is the main reason America continues  to waste so much money on foreign aid.
If Congress cannot pass  authorizing legislation that eliminates AID, it should
refuse to  appropriate any money for the agency's operating expenses until  such
legislation is signed into law. Moreover, international  development assistance
does not work. Countries receiving economic aid  for over 35 years are no better
off today than they were before.  Thus, not only should AID be abolished, but so
should the entire  development assistance program.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Require the President to certify to Congress that any security 
and military aid sent abroad is necessary to support U.S. national  security
interests.</B> The foreign aid account is more than just  development
assistance; it also includes funds for military and  security assistance. It is
widely claimed that this money directly  supports the national interest abroad
by enhancing U.S. influence in  international affairs. However, many of
America's foreign aid  recipients routinely vote against the U.S. in the United
Nations; the  voting records of the U.N. show that three out of every four
recipients  of U.S. foreign aid vote against America more than half the time. 
<B> </B>If Congress is asked to appropriate foreign aid for the purpose  of
promoting the national interest, it should get more than a  promise from the
White House that it will get the job done.  Congress should require the
President to certify that U.S. foreign aid  supports American interests abroad.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Phase out funding for the World Bank, the International  Monetary 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 29 -->  Fund, and the other multilateral
development banks.</B> These  multilateral development banks (MDBs) have been no
more  successful at promoting economic growth in less developed countries  than
has AID. In fact, a strong case can be made that they have had  less success
than AID. Since the 1950s, the World Bank and the  IMF have disbursed over $350
billion to less developed countries.  Most of these countries are no better off
today than they were  before receiving their money. In fact, many are worse off.
The  U.S. should phase out financial support to these institutions. 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><A NAME="Q&AF"><B>Q &amp; A</B>
</A></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. How can you call for cutting aid to the poor at a time  when more
people are living in poverty around the globe than ever  before?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Because most economic aid perpetuates poverty. The only  way poor
countries can break out of the poverty trap is to stop  depending on foreign
aid. In this day and age, poverty is not the  natural condition of mankind; it
is a condition imposed by corrupt  governments which repress their economies.
Foreign aid does not  help countries develop. Most long-term recipients are no
better off  today then they were 30 years ago. If poor countries do not  adopt
economically free policies, they will remain poor, no matter  how much money we
throw at them.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. You say foreign aid does not work. How come the  Marshall Plan, the
largest foreign aid program, is considered successful?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The Marshall Plan was not development aid. It was a plan  to
rebuild already developed countries. But underdeveloped  countries 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 -->  are not rebuilding an established
infrastructure; they are trying  to acquire one. They also do not have the
established  free-market economic foundations that post-war Europe had. Thus, 
while money spent in post-war Europe helped rebuild roads and  bridges, foreign
aid in the less developed world has done little good  because no amount of
foreign aid could provide the degree of  modernization and industrialization
which existed in Europe  before World War II.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. The Agency for International Development has been  extremely
successful in improving child mortality rates, providing  vaccinations, and
helping to feed those in immediate need of food.  How can you support cutting
funding for programs which help to  keep people alive?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Because Americans, as private citizens, are doing a better  job
than government in helping people. Americans spend some  $12 billion a year on
private overseas charities. AID spends less  than $100 million on disaster
relief and related programs. If  America has helped children and the poor in
less developed countries, it  is mainly because of the work of these private
charities.  Private charities are far more effective than AID, which is a 
bureaucracy that spends some 70 cents of every foreign aid dollar  within
America's borders. It is far better to give to private charities  than to waste
taxpayer dollars on American professors who, on  AID contracts, do nothing more
than write studies of foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Isn't foreign aid necessary at least for countries trying to  develop
free markets?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> No, but it can be useful if properly conceived, managed,  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 -->  targeted. Private foreign
investors spend some $18 billion a  year investing abroad. Those private
investments are much larger  than the $12 billion government dispenses each year
in foreign aid.  Foreign investment, not foreign aid, is necessary for  economic
growth. To attract foreign investment, governments must cut  taxes, privatize
business, eliminate regulations, and institute other  similar reforms. In most
cases, foreign governments do not need aid  to implement these reforms (the
obvious exceptions being  former Eastern Bloc nations, which can use it
constructively for  education and training to encourage the creation of market
institutions). 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> <B>Q.Won't cutting foreign aid result in more Somalias and Haitis?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> No. Both Haiti and Somalia are long-term recipients of  foreign
aid. Somalia has been hooked on U.S. foreign aid for 40  years, receiving over
$750 million since 1955. Yet Somalia is  poorer today than it was in 1965. Haiti
has received almost $1 billion  in foreign aid over 51 years, and it also is
poorer today than it was  in 1965. If economic aid is so necessary to create
economic  development in poor countries, why has it not worked in these two 
countries?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Doesn't the U.S. foreign aid program at least help  American
businesses?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Yes, it helps some businesses, contractors, and consultants.  But
this should not be the purpose of foreign aid. Choosing  winners and losers in
the market is not the proper business of  government. Rewarding special
interests with federal dollars will not help  poor countries abroad.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 32 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. You may call it corporate welfare, but shouldn't Washington  be doing
all it can to help American businesses export?  After  all, exports mean jobs
for Americans. 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The U.S. is the largest exporter in the world and would  remain
so without government subsidies, which help only a few  of America's businesses.
Many now-subsidized trade deals would  be made without this government
financing. Yes, some  businesses seem to &quot;win&quot; from government
subsidies, but the losers are  the American taxpayers who pay for these
programs. This  money should be left in the hands of the people who earned it
rather  than given to those who happen to have powerful friends in  Washington.
</P>
<P>
<a name="pub">
<CENTER><H2>PUBLIC DIPLOMACY</H2>
<P>
<A HREF="chpt19.html#ISSUESP">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt19.html#FACTSF">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt19.html#RECORDP">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt19.html#Q&AP">Q&amp;A</A>
<P>
</center><B><A NAME="ISSUESP">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Public diplomacy is the means by which the U.S.  government communicates
directly to the peoples of foreign countries.  Essentially, it involves the
information and cultural activities of  the United States government. Public
diplomacy enables the U.S.  government to present its perspective to people in
other countries  and to provide accurate information about the U.S. to those who
 otherwise would never receive it, preferably in a manner other  cultures will
find credible. These efforts take place outside of the  standard channels of
diplomacy  specifically, outside the State  Department, which conducts formal
diplomatic relations with other  nations. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In this age of information, mass communication is rapid,  virtually 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 33 -->  global, and accessible with
unprecedented ease to a larger  number of people than ever before. Information
can affect mass  sentiment and public opinion in foreign nations, and therefore
the policy  decisions of foreign governments. In certain situations, ideas  and
imagery can have greater impact than bombs and bullets.  Thus, public diplomacy,
particularly the direct dissemination of  policy decisions and the rationale for
making them, remains an  important tool of foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A prime example of the impact of public diplomacy is the fall  of the Soviet
Union. The Soviets could not compete in the  modern world without opening up
their captive empire to new forms  of information and communication technology.
Once that  happened, they no longer could isolate their people from Western
ideals  of democracy, free markets, and individual liberty. It was the 
communication and popularization of these ideals which eroded  the legitimacy of
Communism and, as much as Western  military strength, eventually brought the
Soviet structure crashing down.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Some liberals criticize public diplomacy as a form of  propaganda. They see
it as a camouflage for activities that are improper for  the U.S. government.
This position flows from the Left's  reflexive &quot;blame America&quot;
attitude. Those who hold this view  evidently believe that America's
institutions are deeply flawed, and  that America's founding principles are
irrelevant to nations  struggling to find their way in the chaotic post-Cold War
era.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Some conservatives are critical of public diplomacy as well.  They believe
that America should concentrate on solving internal  domestic problems like
out-of-control deficits and excessive  federal spending. These skeptics believe
that reaching foreign publics  with 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 34 -->  American ideals should be
subordinated to other, more  pressing needs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>While most Members of Congress support official U.S.  broadcasting, there is
no consensus in Congress or in the Administration  on how much the U.S. should
spend on public diplomacy. Nor is  there unanimity on how the official
components of public  diplomacy, such as the United States Information Agency,
should be  organized.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTSP">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     The primary broadcasting arms of the U.S.
government are 1)  the Voice of America, which broadcasts to nearly 100 million 
people worldwide; 2) Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty (RFE/RL),  which is heard
in areas once under Soviet domination; and 3)  Radio Mart&iacute;, which covers
communist Cuba. VOA broadcasts  world news as well as statements of official
U.S. government  policy. RFE/RL reports on events and activities inside the
former  communist countries, thus serving as a surrogate news service for  local
citizens. This vital role is unique because of RFE/RL's  credibility as an
independent, non-local government source of news and  information.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The U.S. Information Agency conducts America's official 
information and cultural activities. For example, it maintains  libraries around
the world and hosts an extensive program of cultural  exchanges. It sponsors
foreign visitors who come to the U.S.  and have a chance to experience democracy
and free enterprise  firsthand. Its research bureau measures foreign public
reaction to  U.S. policies. Moreover, American spokesmen  not merely U.S.  gov
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 35 -->  ernment officials  travel abroad
under USIA auspices to  explain aspects of America to non-governmental foreign
offices.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORDP">THE RECORD </A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Public diplomacy agencies and media have undergone  significant
reorganization since the Cold War ended. The Board for  International
Broadcasting was abolished at the end of 1995 by  presidential decision, and
funding for Radio Free Europe/Radio  Liberty, formerly handled by the Board,
will be disseminated  directly through the United States Information Agency
(USIA), an  independent executive branch agency. This emphasizes USIA's role  as
America's primary arm of public diplomacy. However, even  while public diplomacy
is being consolidated under USIA, its budget  has been severely curtailed. The
USIA budget in FY 1993 was  $965 million. The budget for FY 1995 was $520
million.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Neither Congress nor the Administration has provided  adequate support for
U.S. international broadcasting. For example,  the Voice of America (VOA), the
U.S. government's primary  broadcasting medium, has been severely slashed by
congressional  &quot;deficit hawks,&quot; resulting in the loss of 400 uniquely
skilled  professionals and the ability to broadcast in 20 foreign languages.
These  cuts in FY 1996 come on top of others mandated in the FY 1994 
International Broadcasting Act, which cut 900 staff employees at  Radio Free
Europe/Radio Liberty and 350 at the VOA.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To tell America's story abroad more effectively, Congress and  the
Administration should:
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 36 --> 
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Adjust methods of information
dissemination to the post-Cold  War era.</B> The USIA's audience is considerably
different in the  post-Cold War era; foreign audiences increasingly listen to 
AM/FM radio and watch television, while the number of short-wave  radio
listeners is falling sharply. Therefore, there must be a stronger  investment in
AM/FM radio and television broadcasting, but  short-wave investments may be
reduced to more appropriate levels.  At the same time, the U.S. government must
maintain a &quot;surge  capacity&quot; to reach foreign audiences directly. It
cannot rely on  commercial media outlets to articulate U.S. policy around the
world.  Information dissemination through the Internet also must be  encouraged.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Emphasize reaching the populations of emerging
democracies.</B>  The U.S. has a vested interest in reinforcing the emerging 
democracies' commitment to freedom and both economic and political  reform. The
benefits would be greater security for the U.S., increased  trade opportunities,
and stronger international economies. Public  diplomacy can facilitate this by
providing ideas, information, and  practical experience in the form of
broadcasting, professional  exchanges, and training programs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Provide adequate funds for international
broadcasting.</B> Funding  for international broadcasting should be maintained
at current  levels. This requires at least $385 million for the VOA, $240
million  for Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty, and $27 million for  Radio Mart&iacute;.

</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&AP">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Now that the Cold War is over, isn't public diplomacy,  espe
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 37 -->  cially government broadcasting,
unnecessary?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> America still needs an effective voice to present democratic  and
free-market values in today's competitive global marketplace  of ideas. Other
nations, many of them unfriendly to America,  are speaking aggressively in this
marketplace. The revolutionary  regime in Iran is a notable example. America
needs to be there  as well, engaged in the vital war of ideas, in order to shape
the  kind of world we want.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. America's values can reach the world through CNN,  other broadcast
media, and many forms of popular entertainment.  Why do we need the Voice of
America?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Much of the American popular entertainment that reaches  the
world  rock music and Hollywood films, for example     conveys a jaundiced view
of America, giving some countries one more  excuse to condemn the United States.
And CNN, while virtually  a global network, does not reach an audience nearly as
wide,  diverse, or strategically targeted as the audience for U.S.  government
broadcasting. Nor can CNN speak on behalf of the U.S.  government. We cannot
rely on Ted Turner to give our official  spokesmen the opportunity to tell
America's story, directly and  unfiltered, in a future world crisis. The United
States, as the  world's only remaining superpower, must retain this &quot;surge
capacity.&quot;   Pop culture and Hollywood shouldn't be the only broadcasters 
of American values abroad. America still needs an official voice  to explain its
policies.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Should the functions of USIA be merged into the State  department?</B>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 38 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Some have argued that this would reduce bureaucratic  duplication
and save money, but any savings are offset by the fact  that USIA's basic role 
reaching foreign publics directly  often  conflicts with the State Department's
role in negotiating with  foreign government officials.
<p>
